Title: GETting Conditionally - The Bare Basics
Description: A while ago, a prominent Vercel employee (two, actually) posted to the tune of: Developers don‚Äôt get CDNs Exhibit A etc. It is often that random tweets somehow get me into a frenzy ‚Äì somebody is wrong on the internet, yet again. But when I gave this a second thought, I figured that‚Ä¶ this statement has more merit than I would have wanted it to have. It has merit because we do not know the very basics of cache control that are necessary (and there are not that many)! It does not have merit in the sense that force-prefetching all of your includes through Vercel‚Äôs magic RSC-combine will not, actually, solve all your problems. They are talking in solutions that they sell, and what they are not emphasizing is that the issue is with the ‚Äúdeveloper slaps ‚ÄòCache-Control‚Äô‚Äù part. Moreover: as I will explain, a lot of juice can be squeezed out of you by CDN providers exactly because your cache control is not in order and they offer you tools that kind of ‚Äúforce‚Äù your performance back into a survivable state. With some improvement for your users, and to the detriment of your wallet. But first, let‚Äôs rewind and see what those CDNs actually do. CDNs use something called ‚Äúconditional GET requests‚Äù. Conditional GET requests mean: Cache-Control. And even I, in my hubris, haven‚Äôt been using it correctly. After reviewing how it worked on a few of my own sites, I have overhauled my uses ‚Äì and built up a ‚Äúminimum understanding‚Äù of it which has been, to say the least, useful. So, there it is: the absolute bare minimum of Cache-Control knowledge you may need for a public, mostly-static (CMS-driven, let‚Äôs say) website. Strap in, this is going to be wild. And be mindful of one thing: I do not work for Vercel, CloudFlare, AWS or Fastly. I just like fast websites and I think you deserve to have your website go fast as well.
